#import "../../lib.typ": chapter

#chapter(1, "Narumi Mona")[
  Narumi Mona has long had a deep affection for idols.

  Even since she was young, unlike the kids next door who were roaming freely around
  the streets, Mona mostly stayed indoors sitting through TV shows after TV
  shows with her sister, Narumi Sena.

  For Mona, those times she spent lying on the family sofa, cuddling with the
  soft and tender body of her sister, were pure bliss. It was precisely what
  Mona looked forward to most whenever she returned home from a long, grueling
  day at school.

  As time passed and Mona grew up, so did her sister. Before Mona had noticed
  it, Sena had reached adolescent, a youthful time period that most would never
  forget for the rest of their life. This only became apparent to Mona when her
  sister would return home late, skipping her long anticipated daily TV watching
  session.

  "I’m sorry, Mona. I have to come along with the girls. Just today, please!"

  Sena hastily put on her high heels, while periodically taking a quick glance
  at her watch. With an elegant skirt that was not too short and a pink-colored
  blouse that really fit her, it could be seen that she had been spending quite
  an effort perfecting her ideal image.

  Mona, being a thoughtful girl and someone who did not really care about
  fashion that much, did not pry into her sister’s business. Truthfully, she did
  feel lonely when sitting on the couch alone, but she soon grew accustomed to
  it.

  And as a result, Mona got used to spending her time alone.

  On the other hand, the absence of her sister made it much easier for her to
  focus more on the content she was watching. Without her sister’s presence, she
  could freely pick any channel she wanted to watch without having to be
  mindful, and before she knew it, she had been exclusively watching idol shows
  after idol shows.

  When it came to the things she deeply was interested, Mona paid attention to
  every nitty-gritty detail on the screen. From the choreography to the voice
  techniques, everything about these performances were deeply cherished by Mona.

  She could never imagine how hellish and gruesome their practicing sessions had
  to be in order for them to perform at such a high level.

  The more she knew about her idols, the brighter they seemed to sparkle in her
  eyes.

  Before she had even noticed it, Narumi Mona had become a diehard idol otaku.
  She was much more dedicated to this than anyone she knew, even her big sister,
  the one who introduced her to this sort of thing in the first place.

  At the age of 10, Mona got access to the magical concept of "allowances".
  Since then, the advertisement she saw on TV was no longer a filler section
  between shows, but a great opportunity for her to fetch some new goods. Her
  obsession was no longer limited to staring at her family TV, as she could
  experience the magic of live concerts. It might be scary going to a crowded
  place at first, but she quickly got used to it.

  For some reason, live concerts made her idols shine even brighter than ever,
  even when they were on TV.

  Their brilliance blinded her eyes.

  As a result, she often went crazy with buying the merchandise at the end of
  the performance. She also could not hide her overflowing emotions in the
  meet-and-greet section, only cringing hard at what her face looked like after
  arriving home.

  Over time, the goods she got from all the live performances accumulated to a
  sizable collection. It contained all sorts of penlights, towels, T-shirts
  (some of them did not even fit her at all), keychains, phone cases, etc. Every
  once in a while, Mona would take out the cardboard box full of her merch and
  recall the memories with every live performance.

  However, such an impressive collection came with a cost.

  Mona typically found herself having to kiss her weekly ice-creams goodbye, and
  even though it had been a regular occurrence, a week without her favorite
  treats was a painful torture for this girl. But even so, she still considers
  it a worthwhile "investment". Every bit of merchandise that Mona got was a
  grateful message to her favorite idols, s a precious message of support to an
  idol by one of her fans. Compared to the amount of dedication her faves had
  put into their performance, a week without ice-cream was a mere inconvenience.
  That, precisely, was the sheer volume of respect that Mona had given to her
  idols.

  Not only was Mona fond of idols, but she also loved their music, too. To the
  same extent as how much she loved her idols, of course.

  Even in the age of digital releases, Mona still maintained a massive CD
  collection. For idol otakus, it was a treasure shove, containing all sorts of
  music genres from different artists, not limited to just the poppy tunes
  associated with idols. And this was not even mentioning her massive online
  playlist with thousands of music tracks.

  All of that when she was still in middle school, mind you.

  However, at school, Mona could not just tell her friends something like "Yes,
  I am an idol fan, yeah, like those creepy neck beards obsessed with young
  teenage girls who would spend 80% of their living expense on buying worthless
  idol merch." Well, that image of an idol otaku might be a little bit
  overexaggerated by pop culture, but it was still somewhat creepy in the eyes
  of most teenage girls, or so she thought.

  And since she did not have any hobbies other than this obsession with idol
  culture, she did not have any close friends at school.

  Sure, she might have acquaintances, i.e., people who she could do small talk
  with, but that was the full extent of her interactions with them.

  Sometimes, she would look at the friend groups in her class and have feelings
  of envy.

  _"I wish I could talk as freely as they do…"_

  But it was okay this way.

  Being able to love something was already fulfilling enough for Mona.

  Her smile was already as bright as the sun when she was cheering for her
  idols.

  It’s weird, it’s creepy, it’s not worthwhile? She didn’t care.

  The only thing that matters here is the fact that it gave her power.

  It does not matter if she had no close friends at school.

  It does not matter if her sister was no longer at home as much as she usually
  was.

  It does not matter if the world was against her.

  As long as Narumi Mona loved idols, she felt like she could take on the world.
]
